  <datafield tag="545" ind1="0" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Beatrice and Philip Kalisch conducted numerous interviews in the late 1960s and into the 1970s regarding the training and education of nurses during the 1940s in the U.S., specifically in the Cadet Nurse Corps. This research resulted in a three-volume report titled "From Training to Education: the Impact of Federal Aid on Schools of Nursing in the United States during the 1940s." The Cadet Nurse Corps was designed to provide training for nurses in the U.S. through subsidized tuition and expedited programs and was directed by Lucile Petry under the United States Public Health Service. The Cadet Nurse Corps was responsible for training nurses during the 1940s to help bridge the gap left by nurses sent to Europe. With the Cadet Nurse Corps also came a change in the perception of nursing to a respectable career for young women.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1="2" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The Beatrice J. Kalisch and Philip papers include transcripts and audio recordings of over 100 interviews with men and women active in the field of nursing, specifically in an administrative position, during the 1940s, including the Cadet Nurse Corps and associated programs under Lucile Petry Leone, the founding director of the Cadet Nurse Corps. The interviews were conducted between 1969 and 1976.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="506" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
